00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.869
&gt;&gt;Male #1: All right, welcome to another Author
at Google presentation.

00:00:16.869 --> 00:00:19.680
We're lucky to have Rob Reid with us today.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:25.140
Rob is a writer and technology entrepreneur
based in Los Angeles and San Francisco.

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:30.080
Rob is the founder, CEO and chairman of Listen.com,
the online music company that developed the

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:32.110
Rhapsody music service.

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:34.300
Rhapsody has since been spun into an independent
company

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:36.650
and has over a million paying subscribers.

00:00:36.650 --> 00:00:41.970
Notably, Listen was the first online company
to secure full catalog licenses

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:43.100
from ALL the major labels.

00:00:43.100 --> 00:00:47.559
Rob joins us today as the author of the novel,
Year Zero.

00:00:47.559 --> 00:00:51.039
It's a novel about aliens with a mad passion
for human music.

00:00:51.039 --> 00:00:56.820
However, unlike Listen.com, the aliens did
not secure licenses for the music they love,

00:00:56.820 --> 00:01:01.550
and the novel chronicles the ensuing intergalactic
copyright standoff.

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:04.570
Rob's other writings have included a cover
story for Wired magazine,

00:01:04.570 --> 00:01:08.810
as well as prominent features in publications,
including The Wall Street Journal,

00:01:08.810 --> 00:01:11.820
Business 2.0, and The Glider Technology Report.

00:01:11.820 --> 00:01:15.479
He's also written for countless websites,
including Ars Technica,

00:01:15.479 --> 00:01:16.759
Wired.com and TED.com

00:01:16.759 --> 00:01:21.140
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: Thank you kindly.

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:23.220
[Applause]

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:28.170
Uh, so as mentioned today I want to talk about
two topics

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:31.619
that go together as naturally as peanut butter
and jelly,

00:01:31.619 --> 00:01:37.120
vodka and caviar for you Russians, chocolate
and mayonnaise for you weirdos,[laughter]

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:39.690
and of course it's aliens and copyright law.

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:45.360
And also about my book, which is about aliens
and copyright law.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:52.429
I want to start by showing you a quick video
that at the very last few seconds brings those

00:01:52.429 --> 00:01:58.000
two topics together
as well as I could possibly do it for you

00:01:58.000 --> 00:01:59.440
today at this moment.

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:04.340
And while it does seem probably unoriginal
and even perhaps plagiaristic

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:07.200
to start with a video instead of speaking
one's self,

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:11.840
in this case, maybe not because the video
is of me.

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:15.150
It's just better edited than anything I'm
going to do right now.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:20.819
It's a very brief TED talk that I gave at
the most recent TED conference in Long Beach,

00:02:20.819 --> 00:02:27.480
which incidentally feels like it's populated
entirely by Google employees at this point.[laughter]

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:30.930
It's a quick intro to my perspective on copyright
law

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:36.349
and how, at the very tail end of this video,
it relates to aliens

00:02:36.349 --> 00:02:41.209
and here it is and I will chitter chatter
a little bit afterward.

