00:02:55.249 --> 00:03:01.870
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: The recent debate over copyright
laws, like SOPA in the United States

00:03:01.870 --> 00:03:05.109
and the ACTA agreement in Europe has been
very emotional.

00:03:05.109 --> 00:03:09.440
And I think some dispassionate quantitative
reasoning could really bring a great deal

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:10.740
to the debate.

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:15.219
I therefore would like to propose that we
employ, that we enlist the cutting edge field

00:03:15.219 --> 00:03:18.689
of copyright math whenever we approach this
subject.

00:03:18.689 --> 00:03:23.769
For instance, just recently the Motion Picture
Association revealed that our economy

00:03:23.769 --> 00:03:28.799
loses fifty-eight billion dollars a year to
copyright theft.

00:03:28.799 --> 00:03:33.499
Now rather than just argue about this number,
a copyright mathematician will analyze it.

00:03:33.499 --> 00:03:37.590
And he'll soon discover that this money could
stretch from this auditorium

00:03:37.590 --> 00:03:44.670
all the way across Ocean Boulevard to the
Westin and then to Mars--

00:03:44.670 --> 00:03:47.819
[laughter] if we use pennies.

00:03:47.819 --> 00:03:48.819
[laughter]

00:03:48.819 --> 00:03:52.560
Now this is a powerful, some might say dangerously
powerful insight.

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:55.450
But it's also a morally important one.

00:03:55.450 --> 00:03:59.489
Because this isn't just the hypothetical retail
value of some pirated movies that we're talking

00:03:59.489 --> 00:04:02.379
about,
but this is actual economic losses.

00:04:02.379 --> 00:04:07.919
This is equivalent to the entire American
corn crop failing along with all of our fruit

00:04:07.919 --> 00:04:12.060
crops
as well as wheat, tobacco, rice, sorghum--whatever

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:17.750
sorghum is-- [laughter] losing sorghum [laughter].

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:23.650
But identifying the actual losses to the economy
is almost impossible to do unless we use copyright

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:24.650
math.

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:29.370
Now, music revenues are down about eight billion
a year since Napster first came on the scene.

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:31.730
So that's a chunk of what we are looking for.

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:36.840
But total movie revenue across theaters, home
videos and pay per view are up, and T.V. and

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:39.370
satellite
and cable revenues are WAY up.

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:42.700
Other content markets like book publishing
and radio are also up,

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:49.440
so this small missing chunk here is puzzling.

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:53.240
[Laughter]

00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:56.520
Since the big content markets have grown in
line with historic norms

00:04:56.520 --> 00:05:00.700
it's not additional growth that piracy has
prevented.

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:07.220
Copyright math tells us that it must be foregone
growth in a market that has no historic norms.

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:08.610
One that didn't exist in the '90's.

00:05:08.610 --> 00:05:14.830
What we are looking at here is the insidious
cost of ringtone piracy.

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:17.460
[laughter]

00:05:17.460 --> 00:05:21.530
Fifty billion dollars of it a year, which
is enough at thirty seconds a ring tone that

00:05:21.530 --> 00:05:24.220
could stretch from here to Neanderthal times.

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:25.220
[Laughter]
[applause]

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:28.920
It's true.

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:35.120
I have Excel.

00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:36.510
[Laughter]

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:43.780
The movie folks also tell us that our economy
loses over 370,000 jobs to content theft

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:48.090
which is quite a lot when you consider back
in '98, the Bureau of Labor statistics

00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:52.880
indicated that the motion picture and video
industries were employing 270,000 people.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:53.960
[laughter]

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:57.220
Other data has the music industry at about
45,000 people,

00:05:57.220 --> 00:06:00.590
and so the job losses that came with the Internet
and all that content theft

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:03.750
had therefore left us with negative employment
in our content industries.

00:06:03.750 --> 00:06:04.750
[laughter]

00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:06.930
This is just one of the many mind blowing
statistics

00:06:06.930 --> 00:06:09.000
that copyright mathematicians have to deal
with everyday

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.700
and some people think the String Theory is
tough.

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:12.790
[laughter]

00:06:12.790 --> 00:06:17.040
Now this is a key number from the copyright
mathematicianâ€™s tool kit,

