sued Diamond Multimedia in an attempt to make

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:24.940
mp3 players illegal
in this country.

00:23:24.940 --> 00:23:29.299
Had they succeeded, it would have been one
of those things: automatic weapons, yes; mp3

00:23:29.299 --> 00:23:32.080
players, no,
in terms of legal devices.

00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:39.690
And for the subsequent five years, the labels
not only sued everything that moved in the

00:23:39.690 --> 00:23:44.960
broader market, but they refused to license
their content to anybody who came along and

00:23:44.960 --> 00:23:50.210
said, "We want to create, you
know, a legal substitute that people can buy

00:23:50.210 --> 00:23:51.980
as opposed to steal."

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:54.320
Now the problem with that was many-fold.

00:23:54.320 --> 00:23:58.529
It was basically April of '03 I think, before
the iTunes music store

00:23:58.529 --> 00:23:59.870
