&gt;&gt;male #4: So it seems to me there's a bit
of fundamental distinction between the music

00:30:40.030 --> 00:30:42.450
and the video
situation.

00:30:42.450 --> 00:30:47.039
In particular, I'm thinking about Netflix,
where they have the streaming service and

00:30:47.039 --> 00:30:49.320
they have physical
DVD service.

00:30:49.320 --> 00:30:56.740
And the CEO for some reason wants to get rid
of the physical DVD service in favor of the

00:30:56.740 --> 00:31:00.639
streaming
service, even though the streaming service

00:31:00.639 --> 00:31:04.639
in the long run cannot make any money because
the companies will just

00:31:04.639 --> 00:31:07.340
keep raising what they charge Netflix.

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:09.659
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: Yeah.

00:31:09.659 --> 00:31:17.190
&gt;&gt;male #4: Is there a distinction there, in
that the music streaming business can make

00:31:17.190 --> 00:31:21.620
money,
where as the video streaming business can't?

00:31:21.620 --> 00:31:26.820
Is there a reason for that, or--and is there
a reason why the music

00:31:26.820 --> 00:31:33.889
download business can make money where as
maybe music streaming or video streaming can't?

00:31:33.889 --> 00:31:39.059
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: They're all really really tough
businesses from a margin standpoint for the

00:31:39.059 --> 00:31:44.309
simple reason that
you need the permission of the majors to be

00:31:44.309 --> 00:31:45.809
in business.

00:31:45.809 --> 00:31:49.649
If you're missing even a single major label,
of which there

00:31:49.649 --> 00:31:55.360
are now three, there used to be five, the
gaps in your catalog are so vast

00:31:55.360 --> 00:31:58.919
there's just a great deal of leverage that's
on the studio or the label's side

00:31:58.919 --> 00:32:01.280
when you're negotiating your terms.

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:06.490
Particularly if the whole point of your service
is "We've got everything,

00:32:06.490 --> 00:32:09.729
and you can explore in a friction free way.

00:32:09.729 --> 00:32:12.399
"
And generally speaking, almost without exception,

00:32:12.399 --> 00:32:16.110
and indeed probably without exception, these
deals are cut for

00:32:16.110 --> 00:32:24.309
twelve or twenty-four month basis, the tendency
will be, I believe, it has been in the past

00:32:24.309 --> 00:32:29.139
that as certain of these services manage to
make a little bit of money,

00:32:29.139 --> 00:32:33.460
the labels and the studios are going to see
that, for--because they've actually have reporting

00:32:33.460 --> 00:32:36.529
requirements that they cook into
their deals.

00:32:36.529 --> 00:32:40.629
And they're going to claw back that margin,
and claw back that margin, and claw back that

00:32:40.629 --> 00:32:42.870
margin,
and so I think that the margin dynamics are

00:32:42.870 --> 00:32:48.080
similarly grim in both sides of the business.

00:32:48.080 --> 00:32:55.279
The area in which they're not so bad--and
each business has it's little way of still

00:32:55.279 --> 00:32:59.200
kind of surviving--for us
in streaming it's what they call breakage,

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:02.890
breakage is kind of weird usage; it's a weird
choice of a word,

00:33:02.890 --> 00:33:06.980
for a concept that basically says, "You are
going to have that person.

00:33:06.980 --> 00:33:12.100
God bless him or her, who pays for your
service and really never uses it."

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:14.450
And that's by the way, the way that like health
clubs

00:33:14.450 --> 00:33:19.100
stay in business, and airline frequent flier
programs, and a whole bunch of other places.

00:33:19.100 --> 00:33:22.340
So that's the advantage that the streaming
service has.

00:33:22.340 --> 00:33:26.340
The advantage that download services have
is there's

00:33:26.340 --> 00:33:32.450
some margin baked in, it's not bad, it's probably
like twenty-five to thirty percent gross points

00:33:32.450 --> 00:33:37.279
which a lot of people make a living off of
that so there's something built in there.

00:33:37.279 --> 00:33:42.399
The place that actually I think that has the
best margin dynamics is Pandora, because there

00:33:42.399 --> 00:33:48.879
are essentially government set rates on what
can be charged

00:33:48.879 --> 00:33:54.850
for non-interactive services, basically this
goes way back to the '20's when there was

00:33:54.850 --> 00:34:01.019
the brawl between the earliest music broadcasters--AM
radio in those days--and the record labels

00:34:01.019 --> 00:34:05.640
and the government basically came in and said
"Okay, we're going to determine what those

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:09.220
payment rates are," and that tradition has
continued,

00:34:09.220 --> 00:34:15.260
and so Pandora, by being a non-interactive
service, isn't, isn't nearly as much at the

00:34:15.260 --> 00:34:16.290
mercy of the labels.

00:34:16.290 --> 00:34:20.649
So there's little bit higher margins there,
but margins are kind of lousy, throughout

00:34:20.649 --> 00:34:21.649
the business.

00:34:21.649 --> 00:34:27.929
Because you do, the labels are in a position
to "Oh man, they've gotten bandwidth is a

00:34:27.929 --> 00:34:30.450
lot cheaper and they've done this that and
the other thing.

00:34:30.450 --> 00:34:31.790
Let's up our rates a little bit."

00:34:31.790 --> 00:34:34.619
I don't think these are ever going to be wildly
profitable businesses.

00:34:34.619 --> 00:34:41.619
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Well Netflix, the physical DVD
side of the business, I don't think that the

00:34:41.619 --> 00:34:47.550
labels can actually--
I think they have baked in that into the deals--

00:34:47.550 --> 00:34:48.550
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: Yeah.

00:34:48.550 --> 00:34:53.870
&gt;&gt;Male #4: But fundamentally I don't think--you
can correct me if I'm wrong--I don't think

00:34:53.870 --> 00:34:58.630
that they can legally restrict them from selling
some set--

00:34:58.630 --> 00:34:59.630
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: From selling some [unintelligible]

00:34:59.630 --> 00:35:00.630
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Some set.

00:35:00.630 --> 00:35:04.530
&gt;&gt;Rob Reid: That's a less regulated market
and that's an area where there is more wiggle

00:35:04.530 --> 00:35:10.760
room, but I think there's also a general sense
that in --over the five to ten year period

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:13.260
the DVD is going to go the way of the CD.

00:35:13.260 --> 00:35:19.330
And so that's, you know, to the extent that
there is a differential there it's temporary,

00:35:19.330 --> 00:35:22.540
not temporary in the short term but in the
intermediate term, and then, man, that whole

00:35:22.540 --> 00:35:29.069
business of Netflix separating its DVD's from
its streaming business was really a catastrophic

00:35:29.069 --> 00:35:30.069
error.

00:35:30.069 --> 00:35:33.730
It was a very very strange move at the corporate
level that their

00:35:33.730 --> 00:35:36.990
stock price got hammered for.

00:35:36.990 --> 00:35:42.630
And that's like a whole 'nother topic, but
it was clearly a weird move, as you indicated

00:35:42.630 --> 00:35:48.670
for them to try to split the two and they
learned very quickly that that was a bad idea.

